revision.text:
'''Christian realism''' is a [[political theology]] in the [[Christian]] tradition. It is built on three biblical presumptions: the sinfulness of man, the freedom of man, and the validity and seriousness of the [[Great Commandment]].{{sfn|Tsonchev|2015|pp=1–2}} The key political concepts of Christian realism are [[Balance of power (international relations)|balance of power]] and political responsibility. This political-theological perspective is most closely associated with the work of the 20th-century American [[theologian]] and [[public intellectual]] [[Reinhold Niebuhr]]{{sfnm |1a1=Hyde-Price |1y=2008 |1p=19 |2a1=Rasmussen |2y=1988 |2p=198}}. Niebuhr argued that the [[Kingdom of God]] cannot be realized on earth because of the innately corrupt tendencies of society. Due to the injustices that arise among men, a person is therefore forced to compromise the ideal of Kingdom of Heaven on earth.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} Niebuhr argued that human perfectibility was an illusion,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/king-papers/documents/theology-reinhold-niebuhr-0|title="The Theology of Reinhold Niebuhr" {{!}} The Martin Luther King, Jr., Research and Education Institute|website=kinginstitute.stanford.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> highlighting the sinfulness of humanity at a time when the world was confronted by the horrors of the [[Second World War]], the [[Communism|Communist]] and [[Fascism|Fascist]] [[Totalitarianism|totalitarian]] regimes, and the [[Holocaust]].{{sfn|Woodbridge|James|2013}} Christian realism was in part a reaction to the 20th century [[Social Gospel]] movement that was favorable to the revolutionary [[Marxism|Marxist ideology]]. Numerous American political figures have been influenced by Christian realism, among them [[Barack Obama]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/15/opinion/15brooks.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Obama’s Christian Realism|last=Brooks|first=David|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref> [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], and [[Jimmy Carter]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brianparkhillrarebooks.com/scarce-first-edition-of-niebuhrs-moral-man-and-immoral-society/ |title=Scarce First Edition of Niebuhr's Moral Man and Immoral Society |publisher=Brian Parkhill Rare Books |date=6 October 2013 |accessdate=21 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021221524/http://www.brianparkhillrarebooks.com/scarce-first-edition-of-niebuhrs-moral-man-and-immoral-society/ |archive-date=21 October 2013 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
==Political influence== Christian realism exerted a strong influence on American foreign and domestic policy in the [[Cold War]] era. Many members of the neoconservative movement have claimed allegiance to Niebuhr's philosophy, however, some critics argued that [[neoconservatism]] neglected Niebuhr's strong commitment to social justice.<ref>{{cite news |last=Steinfels |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Steinfels |date=25 May 2007 |title=Two Social Ethicists and the National Landscape |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/26/us/26beliefs.html |url-access=limited |newspaper=The New York Times |page=B6 |access-date=24 February 2018}}</ref>
==Perspectives on Christian realism== [[Gary Dorrien]] wrote: {{quote|Christian realism inspired no hymns and built no lasting institutions. It was not even a movement, but rather, a reaction to the Social Gospel centered on one person, Reinhold Niebuhr. The Social Gospel, by contrast, was a half-century movement and an enduring perspective that paved the way for modern ecumenism, social Christianity, the Civil Rights Movement, and the field of social ethics.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Dorrien |first=Gary |author-link=Gary Dorrien |year=2009 |title=Society as the Subject of Redemption: The Relevance of the Social Gospel |url=http://www.tikkun.org/article.php/nov_dec_09_dorrien |magazine=Tikkun |volume=24 |issue=6 |issn=0887-9982 |accessdate=24 February 2018}}</ref>}}
The ''New York Times'' obituary for Niebuhr, written by [[Arthur Schlesinger Jr.]], read, {{quote|[Niebuhr's] emphasis on sin startled my generation, brought up on optimistic convictions of human innocence and perfectibility. But nothing had prepared us for Hitler and Stalin, the Holocaust, concentration camps and gulags. Human nature was evidently as capable of depravity as of virtue&nbsp;...
Traditionally, the idea of the frailty of man led to the demand for obedience to ordained authority. But Niebuhr rejected that ancient conservative argument. Ordained authority, he showed, is all the more subject to the temptations of self-interest, self-deception and self-righteousness. Power must be balanced by power.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schlesinger |first=Arthur, Jr. |author-link=Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. |date=22 June 1992|title=Reinhold Niebuhr's Long Shadow |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/22/opinion/reinhold-niebuhr-s-long-shadow.html |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A17 |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref>}}
==Christian realism in the 21st century== In the post-9/11 era, a number of scholars have been questioning the overly secular character of [[political realism]], especially in the light of post-modern critique.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Joustra |first=Robert |date=13 March 2009 |title=Recovering Christian Realism in 'Terrifying Times' |url=http://www.cardus.ca/comment/article/901 |magazine=Comment |location=Hamilton, Ontario |publisher=Cardus |access-date=24 February 2018}}</ref> Charles Jones of the University of Cambridge has suggested that international law and normative theory presuppose Christian ethics in the [[international relations theory]]. Despite the Christian realist underpinnings of scholars, originally associated with the [[English school of international relations theory|English school]], the revival of the interest towards religion in International Relations is a relatively recent phenomenon.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Rowe |first=Paul S. |year=2010 |title=Review of ''God and Global Order'' by Jonathan Chaplin |url=http://www.cardus.ca/policy/article/2279/ |magazine=Policy in Public |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=67–76 |location=Hamilton, Ontario |publisher=Cardus |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223220205/https://www.cardus.ca/policy/article/2279/ |archive-date=23 December 2017 |access-date=24 February 2018}}</ref>
