'''Daniel Nettelbladt''' (14 January 1719 in [[Rostock]] – 4 September 1791 in [[Halle (Saale)|Halle]]) was a German jurist and philosopher.

Nettelbladt studied theology and law at the universities of [[University of Rostock|Rostock]], [[University of Marburg|Marburg]] and [[University of Halle|Halle]], where he became a doctor of law in 1744. In 1746 he became a full professor of jurisprudence in Halle, and a royal Prussian privy aulic councillor.<ref name=CHECP>{{Citation | last=Ahnert| first=Thomas | year=2006 | contribution=Nettelbladt, Daniel | editor-last=Haakonssen | editor-first=Knud | title=The Cambridge History of Eighteenth-Century Philosophy | publisher=Cambridge University Press | volume=2 | pages=1207}}</ref>

==Works==
*''Systema elementare Jurisprudentiae naturalis'', 1749
*''Historie der demonstrativischen Rechtsgelehrtheit, von ihrem Anfang bis auf das Jahr 1745'', 1754

