{{orphan|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox scholar | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | name = Khalil Kamarah'i | native_name = خلیل کمره‌ای | native_name_lang = fa | other_names = | birth_date = 1898 | birth_place = [[ّFerneq]], [[Iran]] | death_date = 1984 | death_place = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] | region = [[Shia]] scholar | school_tradition = | main_interests = | notable_ideas = | major_works = | influences = | influenced = }} Ayatollah Haj Mirza '''Khalil Kamarah'i''' ({{lang-fa-at|خلیل کمره‌ای|Khalīl Kamarah’ī}}; born 1898, Ferneq – died 1984, [[Tehran]], Iran) He was an author, researcher and philosopher of contemporary theology that sought to unite the Muslim sects supporting his cause. He studied under [[Abdul-Karim Ha'eri Yazdi]] in [[Arak, Iran|Arak]] and [[Qom]]. He continued his studies of various Islamic subjects and philosophy throughout his life. He worked with the administration in the [[Vatican City]] on various philosophical questions, which he later released in a separate book. He travelled to [[Cairo]] on behalf of [[Seyyed Hossein Borujerdi]] and [[Mahmud Shaltut]], the Grand Mufti and dean of Al-Azhar University Sheikh, for [[fatwa]]. He were an imam for the Jamaat of Fakhr Al-dole mosque in Tehran for more than three decades and thought at the University of Theology in Tehran for five years.<ref>Razi, Mohammad. Hijjah or history books and encyclopedias Qom Seminary - Part Two - Part V. Qom Bookstore solar Borghei 1332</ref><ref>"Astan Qods Razavi Library List", Volume IV, Mashhad</ref><ref>Meshar, Khanbabakhan. List of printed books from the beginning to the end of the 1345 Persian. Tehran: Translation and Publication Board</ref><ref>Reyhan Yazdi, Seyed Alireza. Scholars mirror. Tehran: Publication</ref><ref>Jafarian, rasool. Iran's political and religious organizations and movements on the rise of Mohammad Reza Shah to the second edition of Revolution 1357-1320 years. Tehran: Book House, Esfand 1387</ref><ref>"Ayatollah Kamareyi." Lessons from Islam, Title - Number Nine - Persian date Azar 1363 Page 65</ref><ref>Jafarian, Rasool. "Review of attitudes and activities of the late Ayatollah Mirza Khalil Kamareyi" miqat Hajj, Winter 1382, Number 46</ref>
== Death == He died in his home in Tehran, on Thursday 11 October 1984 after two years of illness. He was buried in [[Qom]], near the [[Fatima Masumeh Shrine]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=A review of the views and activities of the late Ayatollah Haj Mirza Khalil Kamareyi|title=hawzah|url=http://www.hawzah.net/fa/Magazine/View/4789/4819/40141/%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B1%DB%8C-%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%AF%DB%8C%D8%AF%DA%AF%D8%A7%D9%87-%D9%87%D8%A7-%D9%88-%D9%81%D8%B9%D8%A7%D9%84%DB%8C%D8%AA-%D9%87%D8%A7%DB%8C-%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%AD%D9%88%D9%85-%D8%A2%DB%8C%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87-%D9%85%DB%8C%D8%B1%D8%B2%D8%A7-%D8%AE%D9%84%DB%8C%D9%84-%DA%A9%D9%85%D8%B1%D9%87-%D8%A7%DB%8C-%D9%88-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%84-%D8%AD%D8%AC}}</ref>
